        Prior Analytics
        ; see Ch. 4.6.5.1 and 4.6.13.1 no. 32.


he discusses the syllogism and the division of its premises, designates its various figures, and classifies those figures. Amongst the classifications, he distinguishes those that are not linked continuously and systematically and sets them apart from those that are so linked. Then he discusses the results that follow from them along with associated fundamental conditions – that is, the necessary, the possible, and the impossible. He explains the approaches to securing premises of syllogisms that are necessary (
al-ḍarūriyyah
) and plausible (
al-iqnāʿiyyah
), as well as what is more fitting (
al-awlā
), what is more likely (
al-ashbah
), and what is more frequent (
al-akthar
) and those associated with customary usage and technical terms, and the remaining issues of syllogisms. He discusses the figures of the syllogism, variety by variety and type by type.

